WEBVTT

00:04.385 --> 00:06.468
It should be returning.

00:08.790 --> 00:11.333
It's already going in the other direction now.

00:12.675 --> 00:31.017
The best of all collections of any library or private individual on the subject of Cyphers and Codes, including William F. Friedman, who gave his collection to the John Marshall Library.

00:31.267 --> 00:34.292
He didn't collect the early books like the famous and the others.

00:34.332 --> 00:38.058
He didn't have the money on his salary working for the army.

00:38.078 --> 00:41.804
And he told me himself, you know, he's only collecting the modern books.

00:41.965 --> 00:43.086
That's all he could afford.

00:43.948 --> 00:49.377
How do postcards and boys' stories, how does all this fit into your scheme?

00:49.597 --> 00:51.300
You said there's a method in your madness.

00:52.175 --> 00:54.538
How do postcards?

00:54.558 --> 01:04.330
Well, I concentrated mostly on postcards with views of New York City and different boroughs and Coney Island and so on.

01:04.350 --> 01:20.629
And I broke them down into different classifications, famous hotels, the Hotel Aston and Hotel Walden and the Astoria and so on, and streets and so forth.

01:20.947 --> 01:24.916
So being it's a subject collection.

01:24.936 --> 01:27.100
That should be very interesting given here, a public library.

01:27.120 --> 01:28.223
They went right into U.S.

01:28.243 --> 01:29.967
history, local history, and genealogy.

01:29.987 --> 01:31.069
Alphabet, graphic art.

01:31.209 --> 01:31.831
Absolutely.

01:31.871 --> 01:32.693
They have a collection.

01:32.793 --> 01:40.710
And it's really hard for us to be scouring individually to go out and find, you know, or to develop something like...

01:40.960 --> 01:45.826
We could only do one thing or another, but David is like an adult.

01:45.866 --> 01:48.289
He's somebody doing what we do, and he's helping.

01:48.309 --> 01:49.351
And he's got a specialty.

01:49.371 --> 01:50.592
And he researches it.

01:50.813 --> 01:54.718
He finds out more about it, and then he knows what to buy.

01:54.738 --> 02:09.617
In relation to postcards, I joined a postcard club here in New York City, and I attended all the meetings, and I told the other dealers what I was looking for, and I go through their stock to figure out

02:09.884 --> 02:11.767
interesting views in New York City.

02:11.847 --> 02:14.271
I've got a postcard collection that you've done nuts over.

02:14.291 --> 02:17.897
You've heard of Francis Henry Taylor, who was the head of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.

02:18.658 --> 02:21.803
And then he came back to Worcester, which is where I was, and he died up there.

02:22.644 --> 02:24.547
And he had 4,500 postcards.

02:24.667 --> 02:25.849
He's all over.

02:25.869 --> 02:30.036
Whenever he was going off to buy art in Met, he would get postcards.

02:30.488 --> 02:34.960
I went to this auction, not even planning to buy it, but there was no interest in it.

02:34.980 --> 02:40.836
I paid $250, less than half a penny a piece for these extraordinary postcards.

02:41.018 --> 02:44.262
And then the woman, oh, I don't want to get into this, but they wanted to buy it for me.

02:44.282 --> 02:45.504
I said, no, you're going to break it up.

02:45.524 --> 02:47.366
I'm going to keep it as a collection.

02:47.386 --> 02:50.910
And the thing is, if we're big enough, we can keep this.

02:50.931 --> 02:52.613
I mean, it really does.

02:52.633 --> 02:56.618
You know, what went into the stacks is the children's literature.

02:56.638 --> 02:59.261
Well, now we've got this book that he collected.

02:59.281 --> 03:03.126
Do you keep it as a collection, or is it dispersed throughout the rest of the collection?

03:03.226 --> 03:04.387
Well, cryptography is a collection.

03:04.468 --> 03:06.310
Cryptography is a collection.

03:06.330 --> 03:08.072
Do you have a name for it?

03:08.232 --> 03:09.574
We have a special class mark.

03:09.858 --> 03:10.880
What was his name on it?

03:10.900 --> 03:11.541
Dar-K-F-G-F.

03:11.561 --> 03:12.944
Yes, Shulman Gift.

03:13.705 --> 03:15.549
Dar-K-G-F for Shulman.

03:15.569 --> 03:17.613
And then Shulman Cryptography Collection.

03:17.633 --> 03:21.000
He had to create a special class mark for the collection.

03:21.020 --> 03:22.723
He's smiling, so he likes that.

03:22.743 --> 03:28.053
Yeah, of course, I suggested to Frank Madsen, we don't have a special class mark.

03:28.073 --> 03:32.001
A lot of the cryptography books were classified under shorthand.

03:32.420 --> 03:35.584
and other related subjects, espionage.

03:35.684 --> 03:37.186
What was the classification you get?

03:37.246 --> 03:38.568
I think it's Star KGS.

03:38.628 --> 03:47.619
Star K for rare books, and then G for named collections, and then I think it's S for Shulman, but I'm not positive.

03:47.779 --> 03:50.803
I'd like to know if that would help at some point.

03:50.883 --> 03:53.286
We'll talk at some point by phone or whatever.

03:53.466 --> 03:54.527
Definitely all together.

03:54.667 --> 03:57.111
And then the other thing, we're exploring.

03:57.131 --> 03:59.153
You see, we have this classification in it.

04:00.027 --> 04:10.516
the way that Reserve Division was set up initially, American imprints, British imprints, European imprints, and then a couple of different formats, like broadsides and the like.

04:10.937 --> 04:21.526
But everything that is printed after our sort of cutoff date goes into this overall collection called Star KF, which is everything but literature and our imprints.

04:22.066 --> 04:22.767
It's not good enough.

04:22.787 --> 04:27.891
We're going to have to begin to build, and we've talked a lot about this, building special collections.

04:27.911 --> 04:29.713
So to keep material together, just

04:30.048 --> 04:34.112
because you can't just keep fitting it into this sort of overall arching.

04:34.132 --> 04:35.414
What's your direct phone number?

04:35.434 --> 04:36.034
212-930-0805.

04:36.074 --> 04:38.657
0805.

04:39.458 --> 04:42.181
Very good.

04:43.402 --> 04:52.752
By the way, it's such a good collection that the previous president of the New York Public Library, Gregorian Bartin.

04:52.772 --> 04:55.355
Bartin is a strange name.

04:55.755 --> 04:57.117
I've interviewed him for my new book.

04:58.839 --> 04:59.059
Go ahead.

04:59.748 --> 05:02.651
He personally wanted to look at the collection.

05:02.751 --> 05:04.413
I gave him a tour of the collection.

05:05.033 --> 05:05.994
And he said, wonderful.

05:06.034 --> 05:07.035
He was so impressed.

05:08.096 --> 05:22.050
And being that he was a professor of history, he asked me, did Cardinal Richelieu ever have anything to do under King Louis XIV with cryptography of secret code and stuff like that?

05:23.111 --> 05:28.776
I told him about my annotated bibliography that I would look through it and find out.

05:29.043 --> 05:30.706
And he answered his query.

05:31.467 --> 05:37.577
Then the new president now, the clerk, he's getting an education.

05:37.597 --> 05:40.341
We're going to happen to mention that we have a horn book.

05:40.361 --> 05:41.723
Paul's going to love that.

05:41.743 --> 05:42.344
The horn book.

05:42.485 --> 05:44.708
He said, you've never heard of a horn book.

05:44.808 --> 05:45.149
I know.

05:45.830 --> 05:47.373
And I had to describe it to him.

05:47.393 --> 05:48.675
He said, I would love to see it.

05:49.496 --> 05:51.359
He's going to come down and look at the horn book.

05:51.479 --> 05:52.040
That's great.

05:52.280 --> 05:53.262
So let's...

05:54.052 --> 05:55.293
We've got a lot of area to cover.

05:55.313 --> 05:57.355
We've got to talk about your OED stuff.

05:57.375 --> 05:58.576
We've got to talk about... Oh, yeah.

05:58.597 --> 06:00.238
I haven't even gotten to that subject.

06:00.518 --> 06:03.381
That reminds me of connection with OED.

06:03.982 --> 06:10.028
Morganita Lasky, she is the foremost contributor to the supplement.

06:10.408 --> 06:15.213
She has sent in about a hundred thousand slips, citations.

06:16.514 --> 06:18.416
She's a graduate of Oxford.

06:18.436 --> 06:21.119
Why don't you go sit in that chair so I can get you going this way.

06:22.220 --> 06:22.320
Yeah.

06:22.925 --> 06:23.606
Keep talking.

06:25.148 --> 06:28.533
Let me take a couple of shots.

06:28.733 --> 06:31.156
What are you talking about with the OED?

06:31.176 --> 06:31.297
Yeah.

06:31.317 --> 06:51.725
Marlonita Lasky, one of the foremost contributors to the supplement of the Oxford English Dictionary, had heard about me, one of their editors, and she was interested in meeting me.

06:51.745 --> 06:51.885
Mm-hmm.

06:53.570 --> 07:01.341
So I wrote back to the editor and provided my address and phone number.

07:05.007 --> 07:06.749
Go ahead.

07:06.769 --> 07:07.410
I'll pick who left.

07:09.253 --> 07:19.628
And when she came over from London on a visit to New York...

07:20.131 --> 07:33.365
She called me up and invited me to come over to her hotel in Madison Avenue to have tea and scones with her for a visit.

07:35.587 --> 07:36.067
And I did.

07:36.268 --> 07:40.732
I went over.

07:40.752 --> 07:48.400
And strangely enough, the gist of our conversation

07:48.565 --> 07:51.508
It had nothing to do with lexicography or the dictionary.

07:52.810 --> 07:54.592
She was interested in my Army career.

07:55.173 --> 07:56.514
She found herself fascinating.

07:57.135 --> 08:03.182
And all our time was spent with me telling her about my experiences in the Army, World War II.

08:04.483 --> 08:07.086
How did you start working on the OEB?

08:07.667 --> 08:10.691
How did you start doing the OEB?

08:10.711 --> 08:16.277
I always had an interest in dictionaries and words and so on.

08:17.472 --> 08:18.814
communicated with H.L.

08:18.874 --> 08:19.294
Mencken.

08:19.355 --> 08:21.017
He wrote me some very nice letters.

08:21.918 --> 08:29.128
I sent in suggestions for the origin of words, Americanism is a slang.

08:30.950 --> 08:33.374
And I wrote a couple of articles for American Speech.

08:36.037 --> 08:45.370
And then the editor of the OED sent out a general

08:47.543 --> 08:52.107
invitation to people who wanted to contribute to the supplement.

08:53.869 --> 08:57.112
And I became a volunteer contributor.

08:57.132 --> 09:06.542
They were so impressed with what I contributed that when the editor came over to New York for a visit, I showed him my file.

09:06.582 --> 09:13.989
I had a file of a couple of thousand citations, antedating what was in the Oxford English Dictionary.

09:15.250 --> 09:16.251
And he said,

09:17.294 --> 09:20.638
I take all of it and pay you for it.

09:20.658 --> 09:20.918
Wow.

09:21.238 --> 09:22.500
Yeah.

09:22.520 --> 09:27.005
And whatever you send in, we'll pay you for it.

09:27.025 --> 09:30.549
How did you decide what words to go to go searching for?

09:30.589 --> 09:31.350
Tell me some of the words.

09:31.370 --> 09:34.433
I saw the Big Apple and taking a Brody and stuff like that.

09:34.453 --> 09:34.974
Yeah.

09:34.994 --> 09:38.778
Is this stuff that you get, like going through the newspapers?

09:39.719 --> 09:42.202
How do you decide what to do?

09:42.222 --> 09:43.403
I have a very good memory.

09:43.602 --> 09:54.318
for the words that are entered in the Oxford English Dictionary, the earliest dates or appearances in print.

09:54.338 --> 10:12.124
So when I read different books and so on, and I find a certain word, I think may have been overlooked by the Oxford English Dictionary, or seemed to be of an earlier date.

10:12.374 --> 10:13.736
Copy it down on a slip.

10:15.819 --> 10:17.260
Here it is.

10:17.280 --> 10:17.801
I got it now.

10:18.242 --> 10:26.052
Okay.

10:26.072 --> 10:26.332
I got it now.

10:26.352 --> 10:26.453
Okay.

10:26.473 --> 10:26.573
Okay.

10:26.593 --> 10:27.113
Keep talking.

10:27.214 --> 10:28.675
Yes.

10:28.716 --> 10:35.925
I copy down words from various books and magazines and newspapers I read, and I check them out.

10:37.808 --> 10:38.368
OED.

10:39.089 --> 10:41.993
If I find that they have already been recorded,

10:43.019 --> 10:58.239
But when I find out that they haven't been recorded, those are the ones I call to their attention.

10:58.259 --> 10:58.479
Okay.

10:58.780 --> 11:00.702
How do you find the work?

11:00.722 --> 11:04.127
In the OED, you're trying to find the proponents, the first use of the word.

11:04.367 --> 11:04.848
Yeah.

11:04.948 --> 11:09.153
So how do you go about doing that?

11:09.173 --> 11:11.997
Well, I check with OED.

11:12.500 --> 11:15.583
to see if they have any entry for it.

11:16.364 --> 11:22.090
In the original OED, there was no entry.

11:24.052 --> 11:30.338
And in the supplement, they had an entry of about, say, 1922.

11:30.358 --> 11:33.421
It's over here, so you can keep talking.

11:33.982 --> 11:37.445
I like the way you're sitting like that.

11:37.465 --> 11:38.286
Go ahead, keep talking.

11:38.306 --> 11:39.267
It's picking you up.

11:44.427 --> 11:52.816
That's great.

11:52.836 --> 12:13.017
So, in the course of my reading, I found in a book of poems by some writer in the early 1900s, where the writer used the expression, a big apple.

12:13.655 --> 12:20.565
compare New York with a big apple that spreads its roots everywhere, and so on.

12:21.387 --> 12:26.314
So I copied that, sent it in, the OED.

12:26.374 --> 12:32.183
Now in the case of a slang expression like, it's a doozy.

12:33.565 --> 12:34.226
That's one of yours?

12:35.047 --> 12:36.349
Yeah.

12:36.369 --> 12:42.138
It wasn't entered in OED, in the original, or in the supplement.

12:42.158 --> 12:42.919
So...

12:43.422 --> 12:49.088
I sent that in, and I asked them, why did they overlook it?

12:49.108 --> 12:51.791
Why wasn't it entered?

12:51.811 --> 12:57.376
They said, well, we were waiting for your citation.

12:57.396 --> 12:59.198
Can you name a few others that come to mind?

13:00.319 --> 13:01.641
Doozy, can you think of a few others?

13:01.661 --> 13:03.302
Yeah.

13:03.323 --> 13:04.163
And I'll look them all up.

13:04.183 --> 13:04.944
I'll check them out.

13:04.984 --> 13:05.224
Okay.

13:05.365 --> 13:07.707
Because I have an OED at home.

13:07.727 --> 13:07.927
Good.

13:08.007 --> 13:09.629
Do you have a second edition?

13:09.649 --> 13:11.030
I do, with all the supplements.

13:11.050 --> 13:12.552
Yeah, that includes supplements.

13:13.797 --> 13:15.999
Doozy, Brody, Big Apple.

13:18.061 --> 13:19.603
What are some of the others?

13:19.623 --> 13:20.684
Bagels and lox.

13:21.264 --> 13:21.885
They weren't in?

13:23.687 --> 13:25.769
I sent them the citation.

13:25.789 --> 13:27.671
Bagels and lox were not in the OED?

13:28.912 --> 13:30.293
What's the provenance of those words?

13:30.373 --> 13:31.294
How old are they?

13:31.314 --> 13:32.956
I'm Yiddish.

13:32.976 --> 13:35.378
Bagels and lox is a favorite part of that.

13:35.398 --> 13:40.063
I know what it is, but I'm shocked that it wouldn't be in the OED.

13:40.083 --> 13:42.505
What was the earliest reference you could find for it?

13:43.143 --> 13:44.644
On hand.

13:44.664 --> 13:45.665
For Bagel itself.

13:46.646 --> 13:54.453
It was traced all the way back to Poland in the 17th century.

13:54.874 --> 13:56.215
And you found references for it?

13:56.355 --> 13:56.635
Yeah.

13:57.576 --> 13:58.377
But I wasn't the one.

13:58.397 --> 14:00.258
There were others who made a study.

14:09.747 --> 14:13.150
Professor David Gold, who was a great linguist,

14:14.260 --> 14:19.528
and a professor of syllabic languages and so on at the University of Tel Aviv.

14:20.569 --> 14:22.152
He's a consultant for dictionaries.

14:22.172 --> 14:26.618
He made a study of Bevel, and he traced it all the way back to Poland.

14:28.501 --> 14:33.889
So it's well-known, but the dictionary itself, you know, actually hadn't recorded it.

14:34.350 --> 14:36.893
There were many common words.

14:37.775 --> 14:42.141
Was that kind of a hobby of yours, or did you take this very seriously?

14:42.323 --> 14:44.906
Tell me about after the war, the kind of work that you did.

14:44.946 --> 14:46.929
How did you make a living?

14:46.949 --> 14:49.272
I worked for newspapers.

14:49.292 --> 14:50.633
I continued to work for promotion.

14:50.654 --> 14:53.838
I went to work for the Hearst Corporation.

14:53.858 --> 14:54.779
As a present person?

14:55.079 --> 14:56.841
As a kind of promotion guy.

14:57.382 --> 14:58.684
The promotion department.

15:00.226 --> 15:03.930
All their syndicated newspapers throughout the country.

15:03.950 --> 15:06.413
And so what were the years that you left them?

15:06.534 --> 15:08.096
Under Bob Levitt.

15:08.116 --> 15:10.879
He was their publisher.

15:12.074 --> 15:21.185
and had a promotion for the Hearst Publications.

